  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_evenoddadd"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(c)}}
      \item  We assume that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are odd integers and will prove that <m>x+y</m> is an even integer.  Since <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are odd, there exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that
      <m>x = 2m + 1</m> and <m>y = 2n+1</m>.  Then
      <md>
        <mrow>x + y \amp = \left( 2m + 1 \right) + \left( 2n + 1 \right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2m + 2n + 2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2 \left( m + n + 1 \right)</mrow>
      </md>.
      Since the integers are closed under addition, <m>\left( m + n + 1 \right)</m> is an integer, and hence the last equation shows that <m>x + y</m> is even.  Therefore, we have proven that if <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are odd integers, then <m>x+y</m> is an even integer.
    </ul>
  </ul>
