  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_5m_7"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(a)}}
      \item We assume that <m>m</m> is an even integer and will prove that <m>5m + 7</m> is an odd integer.  Since <m>m</m> is an even integer, there exists an integer <m>k</m> such that <m>m = 2k</m>.  Using substitution and algebra, we see that
      <md>
        <mrow>5m + 7 \amp = 5(2k) + 7</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 10k + 6 + 1</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2(5k + 3) + 1</mrow>
      </md>
      By the closure properties of the integers, we conclude that <m>5k + 3</m> is an integer, and so the last equation proves that <m>5m + 7</m> is an odd integer.
      <em>Another proof</em>.
      By Part<nbsp/>(a) of <xref ref="exer_evenoddadd">Exercise</xref>, <m>5m</m> is an even integer.  Hence, by Part<nbsp/>(b) of
      <xref ref="exer_evenoddadd">Exercise</xref>, <m>5m + 7</m> is an even integer.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_3m2"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(b)}}
      \item We assume that <m>m</m> is an odd integer and will prove that <m>3m^2 + 7m + 12</m> is an even integer.  Since <m>m</m> is odd, there exists an integer <m>k</m> such that <m>m = 2k +1</m>.  Hence,
      <md>
        <mrow>3m^2 + 7m + 12 \amp = 3 \left( 2k + 1 \right)^2 + 7 \left( 2k + 1 \right) + 12</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 12k^2 + 26k + 22</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2 \left( 6k^2 + 13k + 11 \right)</mrow>
      </md>
      By the closure properties of the integers, <m>\left( 6k^2 + 13k + 11 \right)</m> is an integer.  Hence, this proves that if <m>m</m> is odd, then <m>3m^2 + 7m + 12</m> is an even integer.
    </ul>
  </ul>
