  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_sec12-typeproof"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(a)}}
      \item Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be integers and assume that <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are both type 1 integers.  Then, there exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that <m>a = 3m + 1</m> and <m>b = 3n + 1</m>.  Now show that
      <me>
        a + b = 3 \left( m + n \right) + 2
      </me>.
      The closure properties of the integers imply that <m>m + n</m> is an integer.  Therefore, the last equation tells us that <m>a + b</m> is a type 2 integer.  Hence, we have proved that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are both type 1 integers, then <m>a + b</m> is a type 2 integer.
    </ul>
